diff:1614457815:1614449453:=77,90d76%0a%3c #foxbegin 210227-203015-554630#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Using Tone in Speech Recognition %0a%3c -> - JacobF%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c Taking inspiration from Dr. Bjorndahl's suggestion to look at feature values and speech recognition, I was able to find an interesting article co-written by members of the Language Technologies Institute here at CMU. Apparently, historically speech recognition programs have forgone tracking pitch at all when recognizing speech, instead relying on word length and assuming that this tends to correlate well with the pitch the user is speaking in. An example they give in English is with 'inCLINE' vs 'inCLINE'. This was done because little to no gains had been demonstrated in using pitch, aside from the occasional system which tailored itself purely to one language.%0a%3c %0a%3c However, the researchers in this article, through a deep neural network, were able to utilize pitch and tonal features to dramatically improve tonal language recognition, and even slightly improve recognition for non-tonal languages. The exact setup is a little hard to follow, particularly because they frequently reference models and results from other papers, but the overall findings presented at the end are hopeful, and the conclusion sums up the research well.%0a%3c %0a%3c https://www.cs.cmu.edu/afs/cs.cmu.edu/Web/People/fmetze/interACT//Publications_files/publications/babel-tonal.pdf%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210227-203015-554630#%0a
